---
title: Miso-Sesame Shrimp & Bacon Ramen in Gochujang Broth with Bok Choy, Cabbage & Corn
description: Miso is fermented anywhere from a few weeks to several years! The result? A salty paste that adds complexity and rich umami flavor to many Japanese dishes. For this big, steaming ramen bowl, miso is concentrated into a base for broth, then simmered with gochujang sauce, bok choy, and napa cabbage. The soup is ladled over springy ramen noodles and topped with sesame shrimp and crispy bacon for a soul-satisfying meal that’ll warm you through and through. You’ll have extra noodles too—perfect for a cozy night in, shared with friends!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/miso-sesame-shrimp-bacon-ramen-0a8e5150.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/miso-sesame-shrimp-bacon-ramen-61d4c73a1123a927e658fc7a-1e30eb52.pdf
course: main course
time required: 40 minutes
nutrition:
  calories: 830 kcal
  fat: 40 g
  saturated fat: 12 g
  carbohydrates: 63 g
  sugar: 10 g
  protein: 33 g
  fiber: 6 g
  sodium: 3130 mg
author: Sara Heilman
cuisine: Asian
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/miso-sesame-shrimp-and-bacon-ramen-61d4c73a1123a927e658fc7a
---

Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(thinly sliced), separating whites from greens. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}(minced or grated). Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb}(minced or grated). Drain @corn{13.4%ounce}(drained).

Once water is boiling, add @ramen noodles{6%ounce}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until just tender, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Drain and rinse noodles under cold water, ~{30%seconds}. Toss with a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon}.

Wipe out pot.

Slice @bacon{4%ounce} crosswise into ¼-inch pieces.

Heat dry pot used for noodles over medium-high heat. Add bacon in an even layer; cook, stirring occasionally and adjusting heat if browning too quickly, until crispy, ~{5-8%minutes}.

  Turn off heat; transfer to a paper-towel-lined #plate{}. Carefully discard all but a thin layer of bacon fat from pot.

Heat pot with reserved bacon fat over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites, garlic, and ginger. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in @water{3 1/2%cups}, @pork ramen stock concentrate{2}, @soy sauce{2%tablespoon}, @gochujang sauce{1%tablespoon}, and half the @miso sauce concentrate{4}(divided). Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low.

Stir in @bok choy and napa cabbage{4%ounce} and half the corn (all for 4). Let simmer, covered, until ready to serve.

Rinse @shrimp{10%ounce} under cold water, then pat dry with paper towels. Season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat @sesame oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Once pan is hot, add shrimp and cook, stirring occasionally, until mostly opaque, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in remaining miso sauce stock concentrates; cook, stirring, until shrimp is glazed and cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more.

Once bacon is cool enough to handle, roughly chop.

Stir @rice wine vinegar{1%teaspoon} (we sent more) and @butter{1%tablespoon} into pot with soup.

> For 4 servings, use 2 tsp vinegar and 2 TBSP butter.

Divide half the noodles between bowls, then ladle veggies and half the broth over noodles. (You will have some noodles and broth left over—seconds!) Top with shrimp, bacon, and scallion greens. Serve.